'I thought, finally, I'm free': Lee Radziwill reveals she felt RELIEF after the assassination of John F. Kennedy - as it is revealed sister Jackie once slapped her across the face
Lee Radziwill has given a rare interview to Vanity Fair about her relationship with sister Jackie Kennedy OnassisRadziwill, 83, talks about how difficult it was when her sister's husband John F. Kennedy became president'There were so many things I couldn’t do when my brother-in-law was president,' says Radziwill in the interviewShe then says that she felt 'free' after he was assassinatedRadziwill went to comfort her sister after the death, and at one point Jackie slapped her across claimed a friend of Radziwill at the timeJackie would later go on to marry her sister's lover, Aristotle Onassis By

Chris Spargo For Dailymail.com


Published:
  11:05 EDT, 27 April 2016

 | 
Updated:
  10:46 EDT, 28 April 2016













e-mail








888
shares

 
         714
View  comments



Lee Radziwill has opened up about her relationship with her sister Jackie Kennedy Onassis and how she felt 'free' when her husband John F Kennedy was assassinated.In a rare interview with Vanity Fair, Radziwill, 83, discussed her life, her famous lovers and her even more famous sister, despite saying it is a subject she does not like to discuss in detail.Radziwill said that when John F. Kennedy became President there were so few things she could do or say, but that changed when he was shot dead aged 46 less than three years into his first term.'There were so many things I couldn’t do when my brother-in-law was president,' she said. 'Finally, I'm free.' Scroll down for video   





 Openig up: Lee Radziwill (above in October) has given a rare interview to Vanity Fair about her relationship with sister Jackie Kennedy Onassis 





 





Who's the girl: The sisters grew up wealthy, living in new York City and spending summers in the Hamptons and later Newport (left in 1970 in NYC, right in 1962 in Amalfi)  





 Noit great: Radziwill talks in the interview about how difficult it was when her sister's husband John F. Kennedy became president (Radziwill, John and Jackie Kennedy at their 1953 wedding)Radziwill also said in the interview that after Kennedy's death she flew to the White House from her home in London to be with her sister during the funeral.She later confided to a friend, photographer Cecil Beaton, that Jackie 'can’t stop thinking about herself and never feeling anything but sorry for herself!'Radziwill told Beaton that on one occasion after the funeral her sister even slapped her across the face.The girls were brought up in wealth thanks to their father, stockbroker John Vernou Bouvier III. They lived in a large duplex apartment on Manhattan's Park Avenue and spent summers on an estate in East Hampton.When their parents divorced their mother married an even wealthier man, Standard Oil heir and investment banker Hugh D. Auchincloss, who owned a massive estate in Newport, Rhode Island called Hammersmith Farm. It was there that Jackie and John F. Kennedy Jr. were married in 1953, and nine years later he was sworn in as president.


